{"formerly":"","seq":"1,10,100,1001,10010,100100,1001001,10010010,100100100,1001001001,10010010010,100100100100,1001001001001,10010010010010,100100100100100,1001001001001001,10010010010010010,100100100100100100,1001001001001001001,10010010010010010010","description":"Decimal expansion of a(n) is given by the first n terms of the periodic sequence with initial period 1,0,0.","formula":"From _Paul Barry_, Apr 16 2005: (Start)G.f.: 1/((1-x^3)*(1-10*x)).a(n) = 10*a(n-1)+a(n-3)-10*a(n-4).a(n) = sum{k=0..floor(n/3), 10^(n-3k)}, with offset 0.a(n) = sum{k=0..n, 10^k*(cos(2*Pi*(n-k)/3+Pi/3)/3+sqrt(3)sin(2*Pi*(n-k)/3+Pi/3)/3+1/3)}, with offset 0. (End)a(n) = 10*a(n-1)+(1/9)*((n mod 3)+4*((n+1) mod 3)-2*((n+2) mod 3)), with a(0)=0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Jul 30 2009Closed form: a(n) = -(1/27)+(1000/999)*10^n+(5/333)*i*sqrt(3)*((-(1/2)-(1/2)*i*sqrt(3))^n-(-(1/2)+(1/2)*i*sqrt(3))^n)+(2/111)*((-(1/2)-(1/2)*i*sqrt(3))^n+(-(1/2)+(1/2)*i*sqrt(3))^n), where i=sqrt(-1). - _Paolo P. Lava_, Jul 30 2009a(n) = round( (100/999)*10^n ). - _Tani Akinari_, Jul 15 2014","mathematica":"With[{c = PadLeft[{}, 21, {1, 0, 0}]}, Table[FromDigits[Take[c, n]], {n, 20}]] (* _Harvey P. Dale_, Oct 03 2011 *)","keyword":"nonn,base,easy","offset":"1,2","author":"_Clark Kimberling_","extensions":["More terms from _Harvey P. Dale_, Oct 03 2011"]}